Bombarder in the name of morality?
NEW YORK – The eloquence has always been one of the main assets of US President Barack Obama.
Yet it now seems that his words have trapped him in a dilemma.
After stating in March that the United States "would not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against the Syrian people" and mentioning last year a "red line" that should not be crossed, Obama will lose face if he does not react forcefully to the killing, attributed to the Syrian regime, of over 1000 civilians using sarin gas.
Of course, the risk of losing face is not a valid reason to attack another country.
But why did Obama get himself into such rhetoric in the first place?
Why this particular line?
U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry is right to call the use of gas "morally obscene".
But torturing children, precursors to the civil war two years ago, is just as much so.
And is it more morally obscene to kill civilians with chemical products than to bomb them, shoot at them, or let them die of starvation?
It is commonly admitted, since the use of mustard gas during World War I, that some weapons are more immoral than others.
Massive weapons of destruction, particularly nuclear bombs, certainly do more damage and more quickly than conventional weapons.
But is there really a clear moral distinction between killing about 100,000 people with a single atomic bomb in Hiroshima and killing even more during a single night in Tokyo using incendiary bombs?
Was it more immoral to gas the Jews than to kill them in mass graves?
A viewpoint, defended notably by Nicholas Kristof of the New York Times, holds that a swift punitive action could convince Syrian President Bashar al-Assad to abandon the use of chemical weapons and revert to "more mundane means for massacring his people."
I think that makes no sense.
The question is surely about the massacre, not the methods used.
In any case, moral outrage, justified as it may be, is not a sufficient reason to go to war.
Mao Zedong was responsible for the deaths of over 40 million Chinese in the 1950s and 1960s.
No sensible person has suggested that military intervention in China was a good idea.
In the 1980s, Saddam Hussein gassed hundreds of thousands of Iranians and Kurds – with the support of the United States.
Is this therefore a legal question? The use of chemical weapons in fact constitutes a violation of international conventions, including the Chemical Weapons Convention, which Syria has never signed and the Geneva Protocol, to which it is a party.
There are therefore valid reasons to consider Assad as a war criminal, in which case he should be prosecuted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), which, by the way, was established by a treaty that the United States has never ratified.
But bypassing the United Nations and launching an illegal war to punish an illegal act is not easily defensible policy.
It could, however, be argued that the "international community," or Western countries, or the United States as the main Western power, must surely draw the line somewhere.
How can responsible governments simply turn a blind eye when innocent people are massacred?
Tolerating a genocide is not acceptable.
But exactly where should one draw the line?
How many murders constitute a genocide?
Thousands?
Des hundred thousands ?
Millions ?
Or does the number not matter at all ?
A genocide, after all, is a question of intention; there is a will to kill or persecute individuals because of their race, ethnic affiliation, or belief.
In principle, killing ten people for these reasons – or even two – would constitute a form of genocide.
The problem can be approached from another angle.
The question to consider before intervening militarily in a country is whether this action has a chance of improving the situation, saving lives, and making the world a safer place.
Yes, violence against civilians, whether through sarin gas or combat helicopters, is a moral obscenity.
Responding to this implies asking oneself: what is the best solution?
Justice and morality have little to do with such a decision.
Like the work of the ICC, "humanitarian intervention" has more chance of producing results in a weak country (such as Serbia, Mali, or Sierra Leone) than in the case of a great power.
No one would contemplate missile strikes on China or Russia in the name of defending human rights or enforcing international norms and conventions on war.
Syria, as many have pointed out, is not Libya or Mali.
It is also not a great power.
But the civil war that rages within it has already spilled over its borders, involving more important countries such as Iran, Turkey, and Russia.
There is no doubt that a regional conflagration would be infinitely worse than the moral obscenities of a civil war.
It is absolutely not certain that an American intervention would reduce the risk of a more extensive conflict.
In fact, some proponents of American intervention – both neoconservatives and “liberal hawks” – seem to want the opposite: they call for war with Iran.
And Obama may have linked the red line regarding Syria to the one he drew for Iran in his mind, perhaps just as thoughtlessly, to prevent Iran from developing nuclear weapons.
What, then, can we expect from American strikes on Syrian targets, when Obama has already indicated that they are not aimed at bringing down the Syrian regime?
They will not end the civil war.
But one missile will suffice to make the United States a direct participant in this war, triggering a resurgence of violence.
Taking this risk to save Obama's honor does not seem particularly sensible.
This viewpoint is shared by many Syrians, including among the rebels.
This is the opinion of most Europeans.
And of a majority of Americans.
This may even be Obama's opinion, which is why he desperately tries to gain time by delegating to the United States Congress the authorization to use military force in Syria.
Since taking office, his relationships with the Congress have been far from easy.
But he needs it more than ever now to cover his back.
